		<group id="content">
			<unit id="101" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Table creation tools and tips</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="102" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Markdown is generally quick and easy to author, but creating tables is a well-known challenge.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="103" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Before looking at tooling to help create tables, it's worth knowing how to author them natively in GitHub-flavored markdown ("strict" markdown does not provide any table support, but GitHub does support them):</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="104" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://github.com/adam-p/markdown-here/wiki/Markdown-Cheatsheet#tables)</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source><pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1">GitHub-flavored markdown cheat sheet</pc>.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="105" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">**</data>
					<data id="id2">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>There are some <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1">web-based</pc> tools that will allow you build your table online and then copy and paste the resulting markdown into your editor.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="106" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Here is one:</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="107" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](http://www.tablesgenerator.com/markdown_tables)</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source><pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1">Markdown Tables Generator</pc> -- It can also general tables in HTML and LaTeX</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="108" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Different markdown editors handle tables with different levels of sophistication.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="109" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Here are some options:</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="110" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](http://www.markdownpad.com/)</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source><pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1">MarkdownPad Pro</pc> has very good table support, but you'll need to pay have the $15 Pro version for GitHub-flavored markdown support.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="111" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](http://atom.io)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source><pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1">Atom</pc> has an add-in package called <pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">markdown-table-formatter</pc> that lets you create a table via GUI.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
